[
    {
        "content": "<p>Stream created by <span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"275920\">John Baez</span>.</p>",
        "id": 260840478,
        "sender_full_name": "Notification Bot",
        "timestamp": 1636482999
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>This is a thread for discussing the use of categories, operads and the like in thermodynamics.   I expect that most of the time it'll be just me and <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"280755\">@Owen Lynch</span> talking about these topics: he's doing his master's thesis at the University of Utrecht on 'compositional thermodynamics'.</p>",
        "id": 260840746,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1636483093
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Next time we meet, I hope:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>\n<p><span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"280755\">@Owen Lynch</span> can explain some of Caratheodory's work to me.  Hey, Owen, can you point me to that long paper of his again?   I'm not finding it.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>I can explain some of Simon Willerton's ideas on <a href=\"https://golem.ph.utexas.edu/category/2014/05/enrichment_and_the_legendrefen_1.html\">the Legendre-Fenchel transform</a>.   Notice that he uses categories enriched over <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">[</mo><mo>−</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∞</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∞</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">]</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">[-\\infty,\\infty]</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">[</span><span class=\"mord\">−</span><span class=\"mord\">∞</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.16666666666666666em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">∞</span><span class=\"mclose\">]</span></span></span></span>!   This is a good sign that our first paper was on the right track.</p>\n</li>\n</ul>",
        "id": 260841837,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1636483508
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Here's the Caratheodory paper: <a href=\"http://neo-classical-physics.info/uploads/3/0/6/5/3065888/caratheodory_-_thermodynamics.pdf\">http://neo-classical-physics.info/uploads/3/0/6/5/3065888/caratheodory_-_thermodynamics.pdf</a></p>",
        "id": 260843475,
        "sender_full_name": "Owen Lynch",
        "timestamp": 1636484145
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Thanks!</p>",
        "id": 260844662,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1636484555
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>You might check out Soichiro Fujii's thesis, mentioned by Willerton, since this thesis defines addition and subtraction for <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">[</mo><mo>−</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∞</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∞</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">]</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">[-\\infty,\\infty]</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">[</span><span class=\"mord\">−</span><span class=\"mord\">∞</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.16666666666666666em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">∞</span><span class=\"mclose\">]</span></span></span></span>, and it seems their rules are <em>different</em> from ours: they say</p>\n<p><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∞</mi><mo>+</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∞</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∞</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\"> \\infty + (\\infty) = \\infty</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.66666em;vertical-align:-0.08333em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">∞</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">+</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord\">∞</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.43056em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">∞</span></span></span></span></p>\n<p>while we say</p>\n<p><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∞</mi><mo>+</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mo>−</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∞</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>=</mo><mo>−</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∞</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\"> \\infty + (-\\infty) = -\\infty</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.66666em;vertical-align:-0.08333em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">∞</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">+</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord\">−</span><span class=\"mord\">∞</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.66666em;vertical-align:-0.08333em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">−</span><span class=\"mord\">∞</span></span></span></span></p>\n<p>But they are studying convex functions, while we've been studying concave ones, so I'm hoping that our approach is just like theirs upside-down!</p>",
        "id": 260846343,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1636485228
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>They make <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">[</mo><mo>−</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∞</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∞</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">]</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">[-\\infty,\\infty]</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">[</span><span class=\"mord\">−</span><span class=\"mord\">∞</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.16666666666666666em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">∞</span><span class=\"mclose\">]</span></span></span></span> into a closed symmetric monoidal category where the monoidal structure is addition and the closed structure is <em>subtraction!</em>   (We haven't been talking about subtraction.)</p>",
        "id": 260846512,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1636485282
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"275920\">John Baez</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/306433-practice.3A-thermodynamics/topic/stream.20events/near/260846343\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>But they are studying convex functions, while we've been studying concave ones, so I'm hoping that our approach is just like theirs upside-down!</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>I think this is exactly right!!</p>",
        "id": 260851052,
        "sender_full_name": "Owen Lynch",
        "timestamp": 1636487412
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Great!!  I had completely forgotten this business when we reinvented the commutative monoid for <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">[</mo><mo>−</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∞</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∞</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">]</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">[-\\infty,\\infty]</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">[</span><span class=\"mord\">−</span><span class=\"mord\">∞</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.16666666666666666em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">∞</span><span class=\"mclose\">]</span></span></span></span> based on our application to thermodynamics.</p>",
        "id": 260851573,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1636487658
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>It's interesting that they're making it into <em>closed</em> symmetric monoidal category (with numbers as objects, and a single morphism from <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">x</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.43056em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span></span></span></span> to <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>y</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">y</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.625em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">y</span></span></span></span> when <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo>≥</mo><mi>y</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">x \\ge y</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7719400000000001em;vertical-align:-0.13597em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">≥</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.625em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">y</span></span></span></span>, which is probably the opposite of what we'd use.)</p>",
        "id": 260851732,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1636487741
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>What's interesting to me is that we can get a <em>closed</em> symmetric monoidal category from an abelian group, taking the group elements as objects and having only identity morphisms.  Subtraction in the group gives the closed structure.</p>",
        "id": 260851855,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1636487788
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">[</mo><mo>−</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∞</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∞</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">]</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">[-\\infty,\\infty]</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">[</span><span class=\"mord\">−</span><span class=\"mord\">∞</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.16666666666666666em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">∞</span><span class=\"mclose\">]</span></span></span></span> is not an abelian group, but they're still getting a closed structure!  They must need the non-identity morphisms - coming from the ordering on <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">[</mo><mo>−</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∞</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∞</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">]</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">[-\\infty,\\infty]</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">[</span><span class=\"mord\">−</span><span class=\"mord\">∞</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.16666666666666666em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">∞</span><span class=\"mclose\">]</span></span></span></span> - to get this to work.</p>",
        "id": 260851931,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1636487837
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>But we also need the ordering on <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">[</mo><mo>−</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∞</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∞</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">]</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">[-\\infty,\\infty]</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">[</span><span class=\"mord\">−</span><span class=\"mord\">∞</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.16666666666666666em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">∞</span><span class=\"mclose\">]</span></span></span></span> for physics, in order to talk about entropy <em>maximization</em>.</p>",
        "id": 260852114,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1636487919
    }
]